ged code.","pos":[10296,10415]},{"content":"A thread is the operating system construct used by the common language runtime to execute code.","pos":[10416,10511]},{"content":"At run time, all managed code is loaded into an application domain and is run by one or more managed threads.","pos":[10512,10621]},{"content":"There is not a one-to-one correlation between application domains and threads.","pos":[10628,10706]},{"content":"Several threads can execute in a single application domain at any given time, and a particular thread is not confined to a single application domain.","pos":[10707,10856]},{"content":"That is, threads are free to cross application domain boundaries; a new thread is not created for each application domain.","pos":[10857,10979]},{"content":"At any given time, every thread executes in an application domain.","pos":[10986,11052]},{"content":"Zero, one, or multiple threads might be executing in any given application domain.","pos":[11053,11135]},{"content":"The runtime keeps track of which threads are running in which application domains.","pos":[11136,11218]},{"content":"You can locate the domain in which a thread is executing at any time by calling the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Thread.GetDomain%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> method.","pos":[11219,11383],"source":" You can locate the domain in which a thread is executing at any time by calling the <xref:System.Threading.Thread.GetDomain%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> method."},{"pos":[11389,11421],"content":"Application domains and cultures","linkify":"Application domains and cultures","nodes":[{"content":"Application domains and cultures","pos":[0,32]}]},{"content":"Culture, which is represented by a <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Globalization.CultureInfo&gt;</ph> object, is associated with threads.","pos":[11424,11534],"source":"Culture, which is represented by a <xref:System.Globalization.CultureInfo> object, is associated with threads."},{"content":"You can get the culture that is associated with the currently executing thread by using the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Globalization.CultureInfo.CurrentCulture%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> property, and you can get or set the culture that is associated with the currently executing thread by using the <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Thread.CurrentCulture%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> property.","pos":[11535,11914],"source":" You can get the culture that is associated with the currently executing thread by using the <xref:System.Globalization.CultureInfo.CurrentCulture%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> property, and you can get or set the culture that is associated with the currently executing thread by using the <xref:System.Threading.Thread.CurrentCulture%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> property."},{"content":"If the culture that is associated with a thread has been explicitly set by using the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Thread.CurrentCulture%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> property, it continues to be associated with that thread when the thread crosses application domain boundaries.","pos":[11915,12189],"source":" If the culture that is associated with a thread has been explicitly set by using the <xref:System.Threading.Thread.CurrentCulture%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> property, it continues to be associated with that thread when the thread crosses application domain boundaries."},{"content":"Otherwise, the culture that is associated with the thread at any given time is determined by the value of the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Globalization.CultureInfo.DefaultThreadCurrentCulture%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> property in the application domain in which the thread is executing:","pos":[12190,12468],"source":" Otherwise, the culture that is associated with the thread at any given time is determined by the value of the <xref:System.Globalization.CultureInfo.DefaultThreadCurrentCulture%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> property in the application domain in which the thread is executing:"},{"pos":[12478,12809],"content":"If the value of the property is not <ph id=\"ph1\">`null`</ph>, the culture that is returned by the property is associated with the thread (and therefore returned by the <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Threading.Thread.CurrentCulture%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> and <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.Globalization.CultureInfo.CurrentCulture%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType&gt;</ph> properties).","source":"If the value of the property is not `null`, the culture that is returned by the property is associated with the thread (and therefore returned by the <xref:System.Threading.Thread.CurrentCulture%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> and <xref:System.Globalization.CultureInfo.CurrentCulture%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> properties)."},{"pos":[12819,12916],"content":"If the value of the property is <ph id=\"ph1\">`null`</ph>, the current system culture is associated with the thread.","source":"If the value of the property is `null`, the current system culture is associated with the thread."},{"pos":[12925,12961],"content":"Programming with application domains","linkify":"Programming with application domains","nodes":[{"content":"Programming with application domains","pos":[0,36]}]},{"content":"Application domains are usually created and manipulated programmatically by runtime hosts.","pos":[12964,13054]},{"content":"However, sometimes an application program might also want to work with application domains.","pos":[13055,13146]},{"content":"For example, an application program could load an application component into a domain to be able to unload the domain (and the component) without having to stop the entire application.","pos":[13147,13331]},{"content":"The <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.AppDomain&gt;</ph> is the programmatic interface to application domains.","pos":[13338,13419],"source":"The <xref:System.AppDomain> is the programmatic interface to 